{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17510101","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17510101"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:24:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11491"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11491","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11491"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.72,0.04,0.1,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4122"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81684"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4122"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11491"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66983"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1315"},{"type":"tags","id":"1571"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"12915"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5097"},{"type":"contributions","id":"5130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/81684"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 23-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic seeking advice about contraception. She commenced the combined oral contraceptive pill six months ago as her sole form of contraception. She has a regular partner and no significant medical history. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She reports missing two consecutive pills from her current pack two days ago, although she took today\u0027s pill as usual. She has not had unprotected intercourse in the past week.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continue pills as usual without additional contraception","Use barrier contraception for seven days while continuing pills","Take both missed pills immediately","Skip the hormone-free interval this cycle","Take emergency contraception immediately"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario addresses the management of missed combined oral contraceptive pills (COCP). When two or more consecutive pills are missed, there is a risk that ovulation suppression may be compromised.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUse barrier contraception for seven days while continuing pills\u003C/strong\u003E is the correct management. After missing two or more pills, the patient should take the most recently missed pill and continue the pack as usual, while using additional contraception for seven days until hormonal contraception becomes effective again.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinue pills as usual without additional contraception\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if only one pill had been missed. However, missing two or more consecutive pills increases the risk of ovulation occurring.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETake both missed pills immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is not recommended. The correct approach is to take only the most recently missed pill and continue with the regular schedule.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESkip the hormone-free interval this cycle\u003C/strong\u003E would not address the immediate risk of ovulation. While extended cycling is sometimes used, it would not prevent potential ovulation in the next seven days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETake emergency contraception immediately\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessary as the patient has not had unprotected intercourse in the past week. Emergency contraception is only indicated if unprotected intercourse has occurred during the period of compromised contraceptive effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Missing two or more consecutive combined oral contraceptive pills requires seven days of backup contraception","After missing combined oral contraceptive pills, take the most recently missed pill and continue the pack as usual","Emergency contraception is not required after missing combined oral contraceptive pills if no unprotected intercourse has occurred in the previous seven days"],"references":["Britton LE, Alspaugh A, Greene MZ, McLemore MR. An evidence-based update on contraception. Am J Nurs. 2020 Feb [cited 16 Jan 2022];120(2):22-23. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7533104/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66983"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11491"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66983"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-26T19:50:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-26T19:50:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4122"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"81684"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}